<subSubSection pageId="199" pageNumber="478" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="199.[721,1314,2187,2615]" lastBlockId="199.[107,1315,2620,3127]" pageId="199" pageNumber="478">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[722,1001,2424,2457]" pageId="199" pageNumber="478">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 110-134 mm, tail 75-84 mm, hindfoot 25-27 mm (ranges from the original series); ear 16-19 mm and weight 26-41 g. Day’s Grass Mouse is a medium-sized species of 
<taxonomicName box="[108,207,2620,2653]" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Akodon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="199" pageNumber="478" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Akodon</taxonomicName>
. Dorsum is blackish brown,sides are slightly paler, and venteris rufous. Ears are blackish; forefeet and hindfeet are brownish black above; and tail is blackish.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="199" pageNumber="478" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="199.[107,1315,2620,3127]" pageId="199" pageNumber="478">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[108,219,2708,2733]" pageId="199" pageNumber="478">Habitat.</emphasis>
Mesic areas including savannas, lowland dry forests, and moist forests of Amazonia, Chiquitano, Campos Cerrados, and Yungas ecoregions at elevations of 250-2450 m.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[108,608,2822,2851]" pageId="199" pageNumber="478" type="food_feeding">
<paragraph blockId="199.[107,1315,2620,3127]" box="[108,608,2822,2851]" pageId="199" pageNumber="478">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[108,370,2822,2851]" pageId="199" pageNumber="478">Food and Feeding.</emphasis>
